WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.410 --> 00:00:05.176
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: What I did

00:00:05.176 --> 00:00:09.111
yesterday, or Monday,
was to describe to you the

00:00:09.111 --> 00:00:14.092
First Law of thermodynamics.
So, let me remind you what the

00:00:14.092 --> 00:00:18.183
context was.
We're going to study a system,

00:00:18.183 --> 00:00:23.957
that's our thermodynamic
system, and for all our purposes

00:00:23.957 --> 00:00:29.937
you can imagine that to be some
amount of ideal gas trapped

00:00:29.937 --> 00:00:34.990
inside this piston and cylinder
combination.

00:00:34.990 --> 00:00:39.565
We put some weights or maybe
some sand on top to keep the

00:00:39.565 --> 00:00:45.052
piston where we want it.
The gas has a certain pressure

00:00:45.052 --> 00:00:51.216
and a certain volume and we
represent that by a point in

00:00:51.216 --> 00:00:56.480
this diagram.
That defines the state.

00:00:56.480 --> 00:01:00.079
That's called the state of the
gas.

00:01:00.079 --> 00:01:03.850
On a microscopic level,
the state is very complicated,

00:01:03.850 --> 00:01:06.394
right?
There are 10^(23) atoms or

00:01:06.394 --> 00:01:10.301
molecules zipping around.
We're not interested in such

00:01:10.301 --> 00:01:13.297
detailed properties.
We want to look at bulk

00:01:13.297 --> 00:01:16.996
macroscopic properties of which
pressure and volume is a

00:01:16.996 --> 00:01:19.670
complete pair.
That's all you need.

00:01:19.670 --> 00:01:24.133
I think I reminded you that you
don't need a third axis for

00:01:24.133 --> 00:01:28.750
temperature because we have this
equation PV = nRT.

00:01:28.750 --> 00:01:31.120
So, if you know P and V,
you don't need temperature as

00:01:31.120 --> 00:01:34.410
another variable.
That's called the equation of

00:01:34.410 --> 00:01:38.620
state.
You can use this all the time.

00:01:38.620 --> 00:01:44.088
Whenever the gas has got a
pressure and volume,

00:01:44.088 --> 00:01:48.250
feel free to use PV =
nRT.

00:01:48.250 --> 00:01:51.958
Alright, so here's the gas.
And then I want to change its

00:01:51.958 --> 00:01:56.532
state, and I explained to you
that unlike particles whose

00:01:56.532 --> 00:01:59.800
state can change as fast as you
like,

00:01:59.800 --> 00:02:03.051
you cannot change the state of
a gas abruptly because if you

00:02:03.051 --> 00:02:04.980
take half the weight off the
top,

00:02:04.980 --> 00:02:07.902
the piston will fly off;
there will be a period when the

00:02:07.902 --> 00:02:10.454
gas is not in equilibrium.
Different parts of it will have

00:02:10.454 --> 00:02:12.180
different densities,
different pressure.

00:02:12.180 --> 00:02:16.026
You cannot represent that
complicated state as a point in

00:02:16.026 --> 00:02:18.762
this plane.
So, what we want to do is to

00:02:18.762 --> 00:02:22.250
make changes which are slow
enough for us to follow.

00:02:22.250 --> 00:02:26.970
So, one way to do that is to
take one grain of sand.

00:02:26.970 --> 00:02:29.544
Take one grain of sand,
then you lower the pressure a

00:02:29.544 --> 00:02:32.070
little bit, the piston will move
up a little bit.

00:02:32.070 --> 00:02:34.365
Move up means what?
Bigger volume,

00:02:34.365 --> 00:02:37.233
lower pressure,
the gas will come there and

00:02:37.233 --> 00:02:41.193
then you can take off another
grain and by making the grain

00:02:41.193 --> 00:02:44.421
smaller and smaller,
you can make these dots closer

00:02:44.421 --> 00:02:46.986
and closer.
It's going to take you a long

00:02:46.986 --> 00:02:51.170
time but in principle you can
make the gas move on some path.

00:02:51.170 --> 00:02:57.663
That is a thermodynamic process.
This process is always near

00:02:57.663 --> 00:03:01.061
equilibrium.
You never deviate too much from

00:03:01.061 --> 00:03:03.909
equilibrium, and it's called a
quasi-static;

00:03:03.909 --> 00:03:08.869
that means not quite static,
but as slow as you like,

00:03:08.869 --> 00:03:14.050
and it is called reversible.
Reversible means that you can

00:03:14.050 --> 00:03:17.090
also go right back to where you
came.

00:03:17.090 --> 00:03:19.639
If you took a grain out,
piston expands.

00:03:19.639 --> 00:03:23.039
You put the grain back,
piston contracts.

00:03:23.039 --> 00:03:27.259
So, you can go down this way or
you can go up this way.

00:03:27.259 --> 00:03:30.129
I've just chosen to,
let's say, go down like this.

00:03:30.129 --> 00:03:34.687
When that happens,
we want to say the following

00:03:34.687 --> 00:03:39.840
thing about the state of the gas
before and after.

00:03:39.840 --> 00:03:43.784
At every point in the PV
diagram, the gas has something

00:03:43.784 --> 00:03:45.660
called the internal energy.

00:03:50.810 --> 00:03:54.451
The characteristic of internal
energy is it's called a state

00:03:54.451 --> 00:03:56.552
variable.
And this is a very important

00:03:56.552 --> 00:03:59.093
concept.
A sate variable depends on

00:03:59.093 --> 00:04:03.900
where you are in the PV
diagram, what your state is.

00:04:03.900 --> 00:04:05.780
It does not depend on the
history;

00:04:05.780 --> 00:04:08.901
it does not depend on all the
things the gas has gone through

00:04:08.901 --> 00:04:11.296
in its life.
If you tell me you are here,

00:04:11.296 --> 00:04:14.807
then we may associate with that
point an energy that doesn't

00:04:14.807 --> 00:04:17.009
look into the history of that
gas.

00:04:17.009 --> 00:04:21.360
That energy is nothing other
than the kinetic energy.

00:04:21.360 --> 00:04:24.637
You'll remember that it's 3/2
kT per atom,

00:04:24.637 --> 00:04:27.710
N atoms,
that's the internal energy.

00:04:30.730 --> 00:04:35.970
You can also write this as 3/2
nRT.

00:04:35.970 --> 00:04:38.862
If you count the molecules then
use Boltzmann constant,

00:04:38.862 --> 00:04:42.130
or you count the number of
moles then use the gas constant.

00:04:42.130 --> 00:04:46.291
It's the same thing.
But nRT is PV,

00:04:46.291 --> 00:04:51.180
so if you like,
you can also write it this way.

00:04:51.180 --> 00:04:54.290
That shows you very clearly the
internal energy is uniquely

00:04:54.290 --> 00:04:56.919
determined by PV,
and P and V

00:04:56.919 --> 00:05:00.560
determine the product PV.
So, at each point in this

00:05:00.560 --> 00:05:03.160
diagram, the gas is a certain
energy.

00:05:03.160 --> 00:05:06.459
But energy is simply that ½
mv^(2) for each molecule.

00:05:06.459 --> 00:05:09.560
You add it all up,
that's the total energy.

00:05:09.560 --> 00:05:13.800
Okay, so we can write it many
different ways.

00:05:13.800 --> 00:05:17.333
Now, the First Law of
Thermodynamics asks the

00:05:17.333 --> 00:05:21.514
following question.
If I want to change the energy

00:05:21.514 --> 00:05:25.515
of this gas, how can I do it?
There are two ways to change

00:05:25.515 --> 00:05:27.934
the energy of the gas,
and the total change in

00:05:27.934 --> 00:05:30.268
U,
meaning U at the end

00:05:30.268 --> 00:05:33.894
minus U at the beginning,
where these are two nearby

00:05:33.894 --> 00:05:38.666
points,
is either the heat input minus

00:05:38.666 --> 00:05:47.649
the work done by the gas--Let me
write it as capital PdV.

00:05:47.649 --> 00:05:54.170
Sometimes you write it as
∆Q - ∆W.

00:05:54.170 --> 00:05:58.468
That's the First Law.
So, you have to take some time

00:05:58.468 --> 00:05:59.700
to understand what it says.

00:06:02.990 --> 00:06:06.025
Notice from this formula here,
the energy of an ideal gas,

00:06:06.025 --> 00:06:09.061
and only an ideal gas because
that's the only thing we are

00:06:09.061 --> 00:06:12.402
going to talk about,
is a function only of

00:06:12.402 --> 00:06:15.019
temperature.
If you know the temperature of

00:06:15.019 --> 00:06:17.340
the gas, you know the kinetic
energy of the molecule,

00:06:17.340 --> 00:06:19.930
so if the number is constant,
the energy is determined.

00:06:19.930 --> 00:06:23.089
The energy depends only on the
temperature for an ideal gas.

00:06:23.089 --> 00:06:25.269
So basically,
when I say how can I change the

00:06:25.269 --> 00:06:27.647
energy of the gas,
I'm asking how can I raise the

00:06:27.647 --> 00:06:31.649
temperature?
One obvious way is this.

00:06:31.649 --> 00:06:35.170
Put it on a hotplate which is
slightly hotter than the gas.

00:06:35.170 --> 00:06:37.949
Then the heat will flow from
the hotplate to the gas.

00:06:37.949 --> 00:06:40.029
That's called heating up the
gas.

00:06:40.029 --> 00:06:43.769
There you don't see anything
happening, right?

00:06:43.769 --> 00:06:45.790
It's occurring at a molecular
level.

00:06:45.790 --> 00:06:48.171
The molecules in the hotplate
are, on average,

00:06:48.171 --> 00:06:50.977
moving faster than the
molecules in the gas and during

00:06:50.977 --> 00:06:52.920
the collision;
kinetic energy will be

00:06:52.920 --> 00:06:54.810
transferred from the hotplate to
the gas.

00:06:54.810 --> 00:06:58.115
That invisible flow people used
to think of as the caloric

00:06:58.115 --> 00:07:01.363
fluid, but now we know it's just
molecular kinetic energy

00:07:01.363 --> 00:07:04.959
transferred from the molecules
in the plate to molecules in the

00:07:04.959 --> 00:07:06.910
gas.
That's this guy.

00:07:06.910 --> 00:07:10.518
This ∆W,
the plus sign of the W

00:07:10.518 --> 00:07:14.990
is the work done by the gas,
and minus of that is the work

00:07:14.990 --> 00:07:18.119
done on the gas.
And that means if you want to

00:07:18.119 --> 00:07:21.506
increase the temperature of the
gas, you're also told you can do

00:07:21.506 --> 00:07:24.110
the following.
Push down on the piston.

00:07:24.110 --> 00:07:28.689
If you push down on the piston,
you are reducing the volume.

00:07:28.689 --> 00:07:32.047
∆V is negative,
minus P∆V is positive,

00:07:32.047 --> 00:07:35.100
and that'll also increase the
energy of the gas.

00:07:35.100 --> 00:07:38.485
Or, if you take a grain of sand
out, and the piston moves

00:07:38.485 --> 00:07:42.172
upwards, the gas works against
the environment and it pays for

00:07:42.172 --> 00:07:45.800
it through its internal energy
because then P∆V will

00:07:45.800 --> 00:07:49.427
be positive and this thing will
be a negative contribution of

00:07:49.427 --> 00:07:52.151
the internal energy.
So, there are two ways to

00:07:52.151 --> 00:07:55.740
change the energy of the gas.
One is a way you can actually

00:07:55.740 --> 00:07:58.820
see by moving up and down the
piston.

00:07:58.820 --> 00:08:01.892
You can see somebody moving it.
It's a macroscopic motion of

00:08:01.892 --> 00:08:04.615
something you can see.
That's called the work done on

00:08:04.615 --> 00:08:07.203
the gas.
Other one is energy transferred

00:08:07.203 --> 00:08:11.181
at a molecular or microscopic
level, which is what we call

00:08:11.181 --> 00:08:13.767
heat.
And the First Law says the

00:08:13.767 --> 00:08:17.822
total change in the internal
energy is the sum of two

00:08:17.822 --> 00:08:21.775
numbers.
First one is the heat input and

00:08:21.775 --> 00:08:25.070
the second one is the work done.

00:08:31.959 --> 00:08:37.294
So, what I did for you last
time was a practice calculation

00:08:37.294 --> 00:08:42.169
in which I took a gas here,
went along an isotherm.

00:08:42.169 --> 00:08:44.230
That means temperature is a
constant.

00:08:44.230 --> 00:08:49.269
That's the meaning of the
isotherm.

00:08:49.269 --> 00:08:54.179
And I want to go from some
initial point to some final

00:08:54.179 --> 00:08:55.724
point.
So, this volume

00:08:55.724 --> 00:08:58.730
V_1 and
pressure P_1.

00:08:58.730 --> 00:09:02.150
This is P_2
and V_2,

00:09:02.150 --> 00:09:05.636
and I want to find the work
done by the gas during this

00:09:05.636 --> 00:09:08.083
expansion.
Well, P times

00:09:08.083 --> 00:09:12.405
∆V, you can see,
is really that shaded area here

00:09:12.405 --> 00:09:16.418
because it's a rectangle of
height P and width

00:09:16.418 --> 00:09:20.186
∆V.
So, P∆V is just the

00:09:20.186 --> 00:09:23.519
area under the graph that you
follow.

00:09:23.519 --> 00:09:26.517
So, the work done,
the sum of all the

00:09:26.517 --> 00:09:30.598
infinitesimal works,
is the pressure as a function

00:09:30.598 --> 00:09:35.344
of volume times dV from
the starting volume for the

00:09:35.344 --> 00:09:38.741
ending volume.
What is P as a function

00:09:38.741 --> 00:09:41.917
of V at a constant
temperature is nRT over

00:09:41.917 --> 00:09:42.610
V?

00:09:46.309 --> 00:09:49.263
Now, I'm using the factor at
every point PV is

00:09:49.263 --> 00:09:52.330
nRT, so P is
nRT over V,

00:09:52.330 --> 00:09:56.899
and this is a logarithm and we
all know how to do the integral,

00:09:56.899 --> 00:10:01.100
as log of the upper limit minus
log of the lower limit.

00:10:01.100 --> 00:10:04.350
So, that's the first successful
calculation of work done.

00:10:04.350 --> 00:10:07.945
You can take the gas on any
path you like,

00:10:07.945 --> 00:10:10.173
you know.
As long as you knew the

00:10:10.173 --> 00:10:12.973
pressure at each volume,
you integrated the function

00:10:12.973 --> 00:10:15.280
from the left limit to the right
limit;

00:10:15.280 --> 00:10:18.047
that's the work done.
For isothermal process,

00:10:18.047 --> 00:10:21.245
it's particularly easy because
the pressure is inversely

00:10:21.245 --> 00:10:24.270
proportional to volume,
and you do that integral.

00:10:24.270 --> 00:10:26.178
This is the work done.
For example,

00:10:26.178 --> 00:10:30.447
if the gas expands to double
the volume at temperature 300

00:10:30.447 --> 00:10:34.491
Kelvin, the work done is number
of moles, gas constant,

00:10:34.491 --> 00:10:36.800
300 log of 2.
Multiply all those things;

00:10:36.800 --> 00:10:41.339
that's the work done by the gas.
If that is the work done by the

00:10:41.339 --> 00:10:44.730
gas, we can also say the
following.

00:10:44.730 --> 00:10:48.490
The internal energy change is
zero.

00:10:48.490 --> 00:10:50.110
Right?
That's the trick question I

00:10:50.110 --> 00:10:52.505
told you to watch out for.
If you're going at constant

00:10:52.505 --> 00:10:54.820
temperature, you don't change
the internal energy.

00:10:54.820 --> 00:10:58.983
So, if the change in internal
energy is zero,

00:10:58.983 --> 00:11:03.429
it follows at every step,
∆Q = ∆W.

00:11:03.429 --> 00:11:05.960
This quantity we call
∆W.

00:11:09.909 --> 00:11:14.302
Therefore, the work done by the
gas is also equal to the total

00:11:14.302 --> 00:11:18.311
heat input of the gas.
We indicate that by drawing a

00:11:18.311 --> 00:11:21.902
little arrow like this;
it's just the way we like to

00:11:21.902 --> 00:11:24.029
show that heat flows into the
gas.

00:11:24.029 --> 00:11:27.639
Do you understand physically
what's happening?

00:11:27.639 --> 00:11:29.866
You take this gas,
you keep it on a reservoir at

00:11:29.866 --> 00:11:32.756
temperature T_1
[T_1 is just

00:11:32.756 --> 00:11:34.909
T].
It's stuck at that temperature.

00:11:34.909 --> 00:11:37.899
If you take a grain of sand,
gas is expanding.

00:11:37.899 --> 00:11:41.264
Normally, when the gas expands,
it does work and if energy will

00:11:41.264 --> 00:11:44.192
go down, it'll cool down.
But you're not letting it cool

00:11:44.192 --> 00:11:46.434
down because you're pumping in
heat from below,

00:11:46.434 --> 00:11:48.139
maintaining at that
temperature.

00:11:48.139 --> 00:11:52.105
So, this process you should
visualize as a piston with some

00:11:52.105 --> 00:11:54.840
weights sitting on a plate at
temperature

00:11:54.840 --> 00:11:58.178
T_1.
You take off a grain of sand,

00:11:58.178 --> 00:12:01.210
it moves up a little bit but
you don't let it cool down

00:12:01.210 --> 00:12:03.399
because you send in heat from
below,

00:12:03.399 --> 00:12:05.200
maintaining it at that
temperature.

00:12:05.200 --> 00:12:08.306
For example,
you got this computer air,

00:12:08.306 --> 00:12:10.262
right?
You blow air on your keyboard

00:12:10.262 --> 00:12:13.215
to blow off the dust.
You know, when you blow the air

00:12:13.215 --> 00:12:16.341
out, the can cools down.
It cools down because the

00:12:16.341 --> 00:12:19.610
compressed air is working
against the atmosphere as it

00:12:19.610 --> 00:12:22.200
comes out and,
therefore, it loses internal

00:12:22.200 --> 00:12:25.543
energy and it cools down.
That's because you're not

00:12:25.543 --> 00:12:28.649
giving it enough time to absorb
heat from the room.

00:12:28.649 --> 00:12:32.380
If you let the air out slow
enough so that in the process of

00:12:32.380 --> 00:12:36.110
expansion it tries to cool down
but the room pumps some more

00:12:36.110 --> 00:12:37.978
heat,
then, of course,

00:12:37.978 --> 00:12:40.923
the can will not cool down.
But, you know,

00:12:40.923 --> 00:12:43.090
that's not the purpose of
buying canned air.

00:12:43.090 --> 00:12:45.061
You don't want to buy canned
air so you can release it at

00:12:45.061 --> 00:12:47.340
room temperature.
You don't care if it cools down;

00:12:47.340 --> 00:12:49.860
you just want the gas to come
out really fast.

00:12:49.860 --> 00:12:55.026
So, if you don't allow heat to
come in, an expanding gas will

00:12:55.026 --> 00:12:56.940
cool down.
Okay, that's also why the

00:12:56.940 --> 00:12:59.290
universe cools down.
Process of expansion.

00:12:59.290 --> 00:13:01.720
Alright.
So, here's a simple problem

00:13:01.720 --> 00:13:05.520
where you can do many things.
You can find the change in

00:13:05.520 --> 00:13:08.490
energy from start to finish.
Zero.

00:13:08.490 --> 00:13:11.704
Work done you find by
integrating PdV and the

00:13:11.704 --> 00:13:15.486
heat input is equal to work done
because there's no change in

00:13:15.486 --> 00:13:18.304
energy.
This is all the stuff I did

00:13:18.304 --> 00:13:20.360
last time.
I also did a couple of other

00:13:20.360 --> 00:13:21.951
topics.
I'll just remind you what they

00:13:21.951 --> 00:13:25.616
are.
I said we can define a specific

00:13:25.616 --> 00:13:28.457
heat for a gas.
Now normally,

00:13:28.457 --> 00:13:33.258
specific heat is the number of
calories to raise one gram or

00:13:33.258 --> 00:13:36.627
one kilogram by one degree.
But for a gas,

00:13:36.627 --> 00:13:40.670
what matters is not the number
of grams but number of moles.

00:13:40.670 --> 00:13:43.833
You have already seen it here.
The energy of the gas is not

00:13:43.833 --> 00:13:47.370
proportional to the grams of gas
you have but to the number of

00:13:47.370 --> 00:13:50.269
atoms you have or the number of
moles you have.

00:13:50.269 --> 00:13:55.067
So, we define specific heat to
be the heat needed to produce a

00:13:55.067 --> 00:13:58.370
certain temperature change for
one mole.

00:14:03.090 --> 00:14:06.293
We take a mole of gas and you
heat the guy and you see how

00:14:06.293 --> 00:14:09.610
many calories do I need to get
an increase of one degree.

00:14:09.610 --> 00:14:13.080
But that turns out to be
insufficient.

00:14:13.080 --> 00:14:17.409
This derivative does not have a
unique value.

00:14:17.409 --> 00:14:24.580
Can someone tell me why it's
not sufficient information?

00:14:24.580 --> 00:14:27.039
You remember from last time?
Yes?

00:14:27.039 --> 00:14:28.677
Student: [inaudible]
Professor Ramamurti

00:14:28.677 --> 00:14:31.996
Shankar: In other words,
when I take a solid and I say

00:14:31.996 --> 00:14:35.830
find the specific heat,
take one gram of solid,

00:14:35.830 --> 00:14:37.927
pump in some heat so the
temperature goes up by one

00:14:37.927 --> 00:14:39.480
degree, keep track of the
calories.

00:14:39.480 --> 00:14:42.601
You are done.
For a gas, it turns out if you

00:14:42.601 --> 00:14:46.610
took this gas in the cylinder
and you pump in some calories,

00:14:46.610 --> 00:14:50.285
it's going to try to heat up
and when it tries to heat up,

00:14:50.285 --> 00:14:52.938
it may also expand.
When it's expanding,

00:14:52.938 --> 00:14:56.639
then some of the energy that
you pump in the form of heat,

00:14:56.639 --> 00:15:00.340
some of it's turning into work
to push the piston out.

00:15:00.340 --> 00:15:02.319
The part that goes through the
internal energy,

00:15:02.319 --> 00:15:04.039
the part that really heats up
the gas,

00:15:04.039 --> 00:15:07.340
is now less because you put in
some heat from below,

00:15:07.340 --> 00:15:09.799
you lose some heat to the
expansion,

00:15:09.799 --> 00:15:11.748
so what goes in to change the
internal energy,

00:15:11.748 --> 00:15:13.610
which is what controlled the
temperature,

00:15:13.610 --> 00:15:16.059
is less than the heat you put
in.

00:15:16.059 --> 00:15:19.179
So, if the gas expands during
the heating process,

00:15:19.179 --> 00:15:22.807
there's a certain energy lost
due to work you have to take

00:15:22.807 --> 00:15:24.768
into account.
On the other hand,

00:15:24.768 --> 00:15:27.745
another person can do the same
experiment of the gas but put a

00:15:27.745 --> 00:15:29.600
pin here so the piston cannot
move.

00:15:29.600 --> 00:15:32.750
Then, of course,
it cannot do any work and all

00:15:32.750 --> 00:15:36.110
the heat you put in goes into
internal energy.

00:15:36.110 --> 00:15:38.669
That gas will heat up more
readily.

00:15:38.669 --> 00:15:40.973
For a solid,
we don't worry about it because

00:15:40.973 --> 00:15:44.240
the expansion of a solid is such
a tiny fraction of its volume

00:15:44.240 --> 00:15:47.293
when the temperature changes
that the fact that a chunk of

00:15:47.293 --> 00:15:48.894
copper,
when you heat it,

00:15:48.894 --> 00:15:51.553
is also expanding against the
universe, against the

00:15:51.553 --> 00:15:54.850
atmospheric pressure,
is a negligible effect.

00:15:54.850 --> 00:15:57.440
The ∆V is so small for
a solid we ignore it.

00:15:57.440 --> 00:16:00.815
For a gas it's very important.
Therefore, for a gas there are

00:16:00.815 --> 00:16:03.670
two kinds of specific heat.
In fact, you can define many

00:16:03.670 --> 00:16:06.220
definitions.
The two common ones are

00:16:06.220 --> 00:16:09.980
C_V,
which is ∆Q over

00:16:09.980 --> 00:16:13.694
∆T at constant volume,
and that's how you denote that

00:16:13.694 --> 00:16:14.940
in calculus [pointing to the
equation].

00:16:14.940 --> 00:16:17.579
The other one is
C_P,

00:16:17.579 --> 00:16:21.002
which is ∆Q over
∆T at constant

00:16:21.002 --> 00:16:24.829
pressure.
So, let me derive one more time

00:16:24.829 --> 00:16:30.814
these two specific heats because
it's worth going over this again

00:16:30.814 --> 00:16:35.162
and again.
The key to all of this is the

00:16:35.162 --> 00:16:37.960
First Law.
The First Law,

00:16:37.960 --> 00:16:43.250
written after transposition,
looks like this.

00:16:43.250 --> 00:16:45.870
Let's put ∆Q on one
side and the other stuff on the

00:16:45.870 --> 00:16:48.217
right-hand side.
In the first case,

00:16:48.217 --> 00:16:52.344
at constant volume,
there is no P∆V term

00:16:52.344 --> 00:16:56.084
because ∆V is zero.
Therefore,

00:16:56.084 --> 00:17:01.350
∆Q/∆T =
∆U/∆T,

00:17:01.350 --> 00:17:05.934
and for one mole,
you remember U is 3/2

00:17:05.934 --> 00:17:09.759
nRT but n is 1,
for one mole.

00:17:09.759 --> 00:17:13.290
So, dU/dT is a simple
derivative of this function with

00:17:13.290 --> 00:17:15.880
respect to T, which is
3/2R.

00:17:19.630 --> 00:17:21.559
What do you notice about this
formula?

00:17:21.559 --> 00:17:25.421
It's the specific heat of one
mole of a gas doesn't depend on

00:17:25.421 --> 00:17:28.468
what the gas is.
As long as it's a monoatomic

00:17:28.468 --> 00:17:31.569
gas, it doesn't matter what the
mono atom is.

00:17:31.569 --> 00:17:33.020
It could be hydrogen,
it could be helium;

00:17:33.020 --> 00:17:35.634
it doesn't matter.
That's why we like to think

00:17:35.634 --> 00:17:39.150
about the molar-specific heat or
specific heat per mole.

00:17:39.150 --> 00:17:41.269
You get an answer that's
universal.

00:17:41.269 --> 00:17:44.249
If you took specific heat for a
gram, then one gram of hydrogen

00:17:44.249 --> 00:17:46.892
and one gram of helium won't
have the same specific heat

00:17:46.892 --> 00:17:49.440
because they don't have the same
number of atoms.

00:17:49.440 --> 00:17:53.326
But if you count in moles,
the beauty of the formula is

00:17:53.326 --> 00:17:56.349
this number is true for all
ideal gases,

00:17:56.349 --> 00:17:58.904
whereas if you took the
specific heat of copper or

00:17:58.904 --> 00:18:01.042
silver or iron,
it varies from material to

00:18:01.042 --> 00:18:03.262
material.
Specific heat of ideal gases is

00:18:03.262 --> 00:18:05.252
very simple.
You don't need to look at a

00:18:05.252 --> 00:18:07.712
table.
Here's the answer for all ideal

00:18:07.712 --> 00:18:09.846
gases.
It's very important it's a

00:18:09.846 --> 00:18:12.457
monoatomic gas,
which is a point-like atom

00:18:12.457 --> 00:18:16.152
which only moves but doesn't
have any internal structure so

00:18:16.152 --> 00:18:18.700
it can spin and rotate and
vibrate.

00:18:18.700 --> 00:18:21.312
If it can do that,
there are other contributions

00:18:21.312 --> 00:18:23.480
to energy, but we're not going
there.

00:18:23.480 --> 00:18:27.019
Now, let's calculate
C_P.

00:18:27.019 --> 00:18:30.471
C_P is
∆Q over ∆T at

00:18:30.471 --> 00:18:33.641
constant pressure.
So now, you cannot ignore this

00:18:33.641 --> 00:18:35.541
term.
So, ∆U,

00:18:35.541 --> 00:18:40.390
from what I did before,
will be C_v

00:18:40.390 --> 00:18:44.860
times ∆T,
plus there is a new term.

00:18:48.500 --> 00:18:53.661
P∆V is ∆ of
PV because P is

00:18:53.661 --> 00:18:55.950
constant.
If P is a constant,

00:18:55.950 --> 00:18:59.075
the change in PV is the
same as P times change in

00:18:59.075 --> 00:19:01.343
V.
But PV = RT,

00:19:01.343 --> 00:19:06.420
so if C_v
∆T plus R∆T.

00:19:06.420 --> 00:19:10.300
If you divide every side by
∆T and take ∆Q

00:19:10.300 --> 00:19:13.505
over ∆T,
then C_P will

00:19:13.505 --> 00:19:17.026
be C_v plus
R and that's a very

00:19:17.026 --> 00:19:20.274
famous formula.
And you should understand why

00:19:20.274 --> 00:19:24.208
specific heat at constant
pressure is more than specific

00:19:24.208 --> 00:19:27.700
heat at constant volume.
Think about that.

00:19:27.700 --> 00:19:31.235
If the gas is stuck at a given
volume, it's easier to heat it

00:19:31.235 --> 00:19:34.299
up because all the heat goes
into internal energy.

00:19:34.299 --> 00:19:38.237
If it is at constant pressure,
you're letting the piston move

00:19:38.237 --> 00:19:42.109
up and some of the heat is being
paid to move the piston,

00:19:42.109 --> 00:19:44.589
only the rest is going to
change the internal energy.

00:19:44.589 --> 00:19:46.401
That's why C_P
is always bigger than

00:19:46.401 --> 00:19:47.970
C_v,
and for an ideal gas,

00:19:47.970 --> 00:19:49.877
C_P is
C_v plus

00:19:49.877 --> 00:19:52.093
R and this number,
γ, is defined as

00:19:52.093 --> 00:19:54.380
C_P over
C_v.

00:19:58.079 --> 00:20:00.206
This is always the definition
of γ,

00:20:00.206 --> 00:20:02.079
where there is an ideal gas or
not.

00:20:02.079 --> 00:20:03.472
For an ideal gas,
we can calculate

00:20:03.472 --> 00:20:05.539
C_p over
C_v,

00:20:05.539 --> 00:20:09.240
which is 3/2 R plus
another R,

00:20:09.240 --> 00:20:13.200
divided by 3 /2 R,
which is 5 over 3.

00:20:13.200 --> 00:20:19.069
So, γ is not always 5 over 3.
You should be aware of that.

00:20:19.069 --> 00:20:21.799
But for ideal gas,
γ is 5 over 3.

00:20:21.799 --> 00:20:24.666
So, this is a review of what I
did last time,

00:20:24.666 --> 00:20:28.314
but I'm very eager that you
guys should be on top of this

00:20:28.314 --> 00:20:31.049
and it's worth doing it one more
time.

00:20:31.049 --> 00:20:36.546
But now, I'm going to consider
some more processes where I want

00:20:36.546 --> 00:20:38.320
to find work done.

00:20:41.720 --> 00:20:44.050
So, maybe I'll start fresh here.

00:20:50.190 --> 00:20:53.450
Let's take the following
process.

00:20:53.450 --> 00:20:56.550
I start here.
I go on an isothermal here

00:20:56.550 --> 00:21:00.514
[pointing at graph],
then I go backwards at constant

00:21:00.514 --> 00:21:05.178
pressure until I'm right below
this point, then I go straight

00:21:05.178 --> 00:21:05.800
up.

00:21:09.769 --> 00:21:11.727
You can ask,
"What is the work done in this

00:21:11.727 --> 00:21:12.240
process?"

00:21:15.960 --> 00:21:21.750
The work done in the curvy part
of it is all of this.

00:21:21.750 --> 00:21:26.740
That's in the part AB.
In the part BC,

00:21:26.740 --> 00:21:31.302
work done is the area of this
rectangle but it's counted as

00:21:31.302 --> 00:21:35.000
negative, because a gas is being
compressed.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:37.189
Or, if you like,
it's at some constant pressure

00:21:37.189 --> 00:21:39.759
but the change in volume is
negative for every step.

00:21:39.759 --> 00:21:42.676
So, even though the work done
is said to be the area,

00:21:42.676 --> 00:21:44.640
you've got to keep track of
sign.

00:21:44.640 --> 00:21:47.829
If you're compressing the gas,
P∆V is negative.

00:21:47.829 --> 00:21:52.047
Therefore, in the part
BC, we must take away the

00:21:52.047 --> 00:21:56.577
shaded region and CA,
no work is done because volume

00:21:56.577 --> 00:22:00.444
is not changing.
Area under the vertical line is

00:22:00.444 --> 00:22:02.680
zero.
So, you can see that in this

00:22:02.680 --> 00:22:06.390
full cycle, when I go from
A to B to C

00:22:06.390 --> 00:22:09.687
back to A,
the work done is the area

00:22:09.687 --> 00:22:13.320
enclosed by the loop in the
PV plane.

00:22:17.470 --> 00:22:22.786
That's a very useful result.
We say the work done in a

00:22:22.786 --> 00:22:27.069
cycle, there's a symbol we like
to use.

00:22:27.069 --> 00:22:29.937
This curly thing on the
integral means taken around a

00:22:29.937 --> 00:22:30.710
closed loop.

00:22:34.650 --> 00:22:38.138
But you guys have to be little
careful when you write this,

00:22:38.138 --> 00:22:41.446
because somebody else can do
the following thing to gas,

00:22:41.446 --> 00:22:44.233
do exactly the opposite.
Come down like this,

00:22:44.233 --> 00:22:46.550
go down like this,
and go down like that.

00:22:46.550 --> 00:22:51.390
Go up like that.
The opposite way.

00:22:51.390 --> 00:22:54.618
In this case,
the work done is considered

00:22:54.618 --> 00:22:58.250
positive because the part of it,
AB,

00:22:58.250 --> 00:23:00.991
is taller than the BC at
point Y,

00:23:00.991 --> 00:23:04.134
so the net work is positive.
Here, it's the same amount of

00:23:04.134 --> 00:23:05.769
work but the net work is
negative.

00:23:05.769 --> 00:23:10.933
So, you've got to be careful
that you describe the sense in

00:23:10.933 --> 00:23:14.114
which you do the loop.
So, the same loop,

00:23:14.114 --> 00:23:16.493
as a geometrical figure,
as the same area,

00:23:16.493 --> 00:23:19.743
but the work done by the gas is
positive in this case and

00:23:19.743 --> 00:23:22.837
negative in this case,
and you can use common sense to

00:23:22.837 --> 00:23:24.759
find out if it's positive or
negative.

00:23:24.759 --> 00:23:29.250
But here is another very
interesting result.

00:23:29.250 --> 00:23:34.030
Let's go to the full cycle and
ask, "What's the change in U?"

00:23:40.010 --> 00:23:43.686
Yes?
Student: [inaudible]

00:23:43.686 --> 00:23:47.789
Professor Ramamurti
Shankar: Right.

00:23:47.789 --> 00:23:50.170
His answer was PV is the
same.

00:23:50.170 --> 00:23:53.158
And more generally,
even if it's not an ideal gas,

00:23:53.158 --> 00:23:55.720
it's a gas made up of whatever
you like.

00:23:55.720 --> 00:23:58.844
It's any system.
If you return the system back

00:23:58.844 --> 00:24:02.510
to the same state,
the internal energy returns to

00:24:02.510 --> 00:24:05.110
that value.
That's what I meant by internal

00:24:05.110 --> 00:24:07.529
energy doesn't depend on the
history of the gas.

00:24:07.529 --> 00:24:09.555
For example,
you can take the cylinder,

00:24:09.555 --> 00:24:11.687
you leave it alone,
I measure the energy,

00:24:11.687 --> 00:24:13.819
I go outside the room and come
back.

00:24:13.819 --> 00:24:16.328
In the meantime,
you took it on a loop and

00:24:16.328 --> 00:24:18.364
brought it back.
I will not know,

00:24:18.364 --> 00:24:21.167
and I don't care because as far
as I'm concerned,

00:24:21.167 --> 00:24:24.380
if P and V are
back to where they are;

00:24:24.380 --> 00:24:27.339
the gas is back to where it is;
energy is back to where it is.

00:24:27.339 --> 00:24:29.819
So, the change in the internal
energy is zero.

00:24:29.819 --> 00:24:34.190
That means the work done and
the heat input are the same.

00:24:34.190 --> 00:24:37.851
So, let's be very clear.
If you guys do problems,

00:24:37.851 --> 00:24:40.460
I don't want you to lose points
for sign mistake.

00:24:40.460 --> 00:24:43.865
W is always the work
done and Q is always the

00:24:43.865 --> 00:24:45.040
heat into the gas.

00:24:50.259 --> 00:24:54.710
So, this is a gas here which
has done some work and some heat

00:24:54.710 --> 00:24:59.284
that's been put into the gas,
and the two have to be equal

00:24:59.284 --> 00:25:03.019
because the energy doesn't
change in the end.

00:25:03.019 --> 00:25:06.851
Now, that leads to a very,
very subtle and interesting

00:25:06.851 --> 00:25:09.884
point.
There is a very clear notion of

00:25:09.884 --> 00:25:13.680
what is the energy in the gas.
There's a unique answer.

00:25:13.680 --> 00:25:16.319
There's no notion of what is
the heat in the gas.

00:25:16.319 --> 00:25:18.841
You look at a gas and you
cannot say this is the heat in

00:25:18.841 --> 00:25:20.390
the gas.
That makes no sense.

00:25:20.390 --> 00:25:25.148
Try to understand why.
Because if you say there's some

00:25:25.148 --> 00:25:28.065
amount of heat in the gas,
okay, whatever you want,

00:25:28.065 --> 00:25:30.515
some number,
I do the cycle and I come back

00:25:30.515 --> 00:25:33.526
to exactly where I am.
I'll put in some amount of heat

00:25:33.526 --> 00:25:36.898
Q, which is non-zero.
So, if there's anything called

00:25:36.898 --> 00:25:40.278
the heat in the gas,
it has changed by an amount of

00:25:40.278 --> 00:25:42.982
Q.
That's why there's no notion of

00:25:42.982 --> 00:25:45.180
heat in the gas or work in the
gas.

00:25:45.180 --> 00:25:49.196
There's only energy in the gas.
A state variable returns to its

00:25:49.196 --> 00:25:51.992
original value and when you go
on closed loop,

00:25:51.992 --> 00:25:54.230
the change should add up to
zero.

00:25:54.230 --> 00:25:57.024
That's not true for work,
that's not true for heat,

00:25:57.024 --> 00:25:58.980
but it's true for the
difference.

00:25:58.980 --> 00:26:01.410
That defines an internal state
variable.

00:26:01.410 --> 00:26:07.548
Okay, now I'm going to consider
a new process which is of

00:26:07.548 --> 00:26:11.510
special importance.
So, the processes I've

00:26:11.510 --> 00:26:15.509
considered so far are
isothermal, at constant pressure

00:26:15.509 --> 00:26:19.328
is called isobaric,
and I don't know the name for

00:26:19.328 --> 00:26:22.825
constant volume,
but no work is done at constant

00:26:22.825 --> 00:26:26.057
volume.
Now, I'm going to consider the

00:26:26.057 --> 00:26:28.960
last process very,
very important.

00:26:28.960 --> 00:26:30.030
It's called adiabatic.

00:26:33.359 --> 00:26:38.119
Adiabatic process is in which
the gas changes its volume but

00:26:38.119 --> 00:26:42.314
it's completely thermally
isolated, so ∆Q is

00:26:42.314 --> 00:26:44.747
zero.
You wrap this guy in a blanket

00:26:44.747 --> 00:26:47.988
and you do things to it.
No heat can flow into the gas

00:26:47.988 --> 00:26:50.933
or out of the gas.
That's called an adiabatic

00:26:50.933 --> 00:26:53.769
process.
Isothermal is quite different.

00:26:53.769 --> 00:26:57.048
Isothermal, you keep it on a
hotplate at a given temperature

00:26:57.048 --> 00:27:00.048
and as the volume changes,
say as the volume increases,

00:27:00.048 --> 00:27:03.244
heat comes in from below.
Or, when you compress it and

00:27:03.244 --> 00:27:06.300
you don't want it to heat up,
heat is rejected below.

00:27:06.300 --> 00:27:09.567
But this is not the case here.
In an adiabatic process,

00:27:09.567 --> 00:27:12.555
if you let the gas expand you
thermally isolate it from

00:27:12.555 --> 00:27:15.142
everything.
So, you should think about

00:27:15.142 --> 00:27:18.000
what'll happen to a gas if I
start here.

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:21.670
That's what isothermal is.
What do you think will happen?

00:27:21.670 --> 00:27:25.275
So, let's draw a few isotherms.
This is temperature,

00:27:25.275 --> 00:27:26.640
say T = 300.

00:27:30.030 --> 00:27:37.430
This is T equal to what?
More than 300 or less than 300?

00:27:37.430 --> 00:27:38.870
Student: Less.
Professor Ramamurti

00:27:38.870 --> 00:27:40.570
Shankar: Less.
And why do I say less?

00:27:40.570 --> 00:27:43.924
You take any point here;
it's got the same volume but

00:27:43.924 --> 00:27:46.823
lower pressure,
so P times V is

00:27:46.823 --> 00:27:49.750
less.
So, this may be T = 200.

00:27:49.750 --> 00:27:54.042
If I start here,
now I let the gas expand

00:27:54.042 --> 00:27:57.389
adiabatically.
That means I pull out the

00:27:57.389 --> 00:28:00.126
grains of sand,
the gas expands against the

00:28:00.126 --> 00:28:03.320
atmosphere, but no heat is
allowed to come in.

00:28:03.320 --> 00:28:06.630
Think about what that means.
Gas is pushing the piston.

00:28:06.630 --> 00:28:10.094
Gas is doing some work.
It'll pay for it through its

00:28:10.094 --> 00:28:14.755
own internal energy.
Internal energy will go down

00:28:14.755 --> 00:28:19.829
and that means temperature will
go down.

00:28:19.829 --> 00:28:23.524
So, what you will be doing is
you'll be cascading down from

00:28:23.524 --> 00:28:27.343
one isotherm to another,
plummeting down in temperature

00:28:27.343 --> 00:28:30.588
until you come and stop
somewhere at the lower

00:28:30.588 --> 00:28:33.368
temperature.
So, an adiabatic process will

00:28:33.368 --> 00:28:36.824
cross from one isotherm to the
next to the next to the next,

00:28:36.824 --> 00:28:38.230
changing temperature.

00:28:41.529 --> 00:28:45.344
Another way to say this is that
the drop in pressure for a given

00:28:45.344 --> 00:28:48.607
drop in increase in volume,
it would be more precipitous

00:28:48.607 --> 00:28:51.675
for adiabatic because it's
expanding but there's no energy

00:28:51.675 --> 00:28:54.367
coming into the form of heat so
