01:00:21.090 --> 01:00:22.626
It's not on top of a reservoir
of temperature

01:00:22.626 --> 01:00:24.860
T_1.
It's completely isolated.

01:00:24.860 --> 01:00:27.360
Take out even more grains of
sand.

01:00:27.360 --> 01:00:30.030
Now, it's expanding without any
energy coming in.

01:00:30.030 --> 01:00:31.780
It cools down to
T_2.

01:00:31.780 --> 01:00:36.279
This is the point C.
Now, you put the grains of sand

01:00:36.279 --> 01:00:39.730
back, but it's still on a hot
reservoir at

01:00:39.730 --> 01:00:42.745
T_2.
I mean, the cold reservoir of

01:00:42.745 --> 01:00:44.728
T_2.
Put the grains of sand back,

01:00:44.728 --> 01:00:47.229
temperature is locked in at
T_2 until you

01:00:47.229 --> 01:00:50.091
come here.
Then, you isolate the gas and

01:00:50.091 --> 01:00:54.989
put more grains of sand back
until you come back to A.

01:00:54.989 --> 01:00:58.518
Obviously, such a path exists
because of the way isothermals

01:00:58.518 --> 01:01:01.150
and adiabatics are in the
PV plane.

01:01:01.150 --> 01:01:04.491
That's the Carnot cycle,
and the important part of the

01:01:04.491 --> 01:01:06.949
Carnot cycle is that it's
reversible.

01:01:06.949 --> 01:01:10.427
It's reversible because at
every stage, when you took a

01:01:10.427 --> 01:01:13.968
grain of sand out you can put it
back and you can run it

01:01:13.968 --> 01:01:17.219
backwards.
So, it can also run backwards.

01:01:17.219 --> 01:01:21.429
The Carnot engine looks like
this.

01:01:21.429 --> 01:01:23.553
Here is the engine,
it takes some heat

01:01:23.553 --> 01:01:25.791
Q_1 from a
reservoir of

01:01:25.791 --> 01:01:29.119
T_1 that
delivers some work W;

01:01:29.119 --> 01:01:30.464
it rejects some heat
Q_2,

01:01:30.464 --> 01:01:31.710
of temperature
T_2.

01:01:35.179 --> 01:01:37.800
This is the model of a steam
engine.

01:01:37.800 --> 01:01:40.949
Suppose you run the Carnot
engine backwards.

01:01:40.949 --> 01:01:45.032
By the way, the work done by
